instruction:
Computer Skills

This section of the test contains multiple-choice questions, which you must answer by using your computer mouse to select the correct response. Upon answering a question, you can go to the next question by clicking the Next button on the Menu bar.

During this section of the test, if you choose you may skip an item and then later return to that item.

When you are finished, select Submit from the Menu bar. Your Test Administrator may have set a time limit for this test section. If there is a time limit, you will be told how much time you have. If a time limit has been set for this section of the test, you will notice a countdown timer on the Header of the screen, showing the amount of time remaining to complete this section of the test.

questions.questionText: Which of the following forms of portable storage media is plugged into an USB port?

Which of the following hardware components is an input device?

Which of the following computer components allows a computer to wirelessly connect to the internet?
Which of the following files is likely exceed the storage capabilities of a 516MB flash drive?
Which of the following is the largest volume of information?
Which of the following methods will ensure that the computer is properly shut down and minimized the likelihood of corrupting the hard drive?

options.text: Turn off the computer by placing it into sleep/hibernation mode.
Turn off the computer using the shutdown feature within the operating system.
Turn off the computer by holding down the power button.
Turn off the computer by unplugging it from the power source.

questions.questionText: Which of the following media storage formats stores information by using a laser to optically burn information onto the storage media?

In most cases, what will occur when a file is clicked twice in rapid succession with the left mouse button?
In most cases, what will occur when a file is clicked once with the right mouse button?

options.text: A menu related to the file is opened.

questions.questionText: In general, what will occur when a folder is deleted?

options.text: The folder is permanently removed and becomes unrecoverable.
The folder is restored in the root directory.
The folder is moved to another area so it can be restored if necessary.
The folder is copied to another area and becomes unrecoverable.

questions.questionText: What occurs when you select, drag, and drop a file over to the Recycle Bin?

options.text: The selected file is moved into the Recycle Bin.
The selected file is permanently deleted.
The selected file is copied to the clipboard.
The selected file is converted to a compressed file.

questions.questionText: Which of the following options best describes what is meant by "double clicking" the mouse?

options.text: Two clicks in rapid succession, usually meant to open a file or start a program.
Two clicks in rapid succession, usually meant to delete a file.
Two clicks in rapid succession, usually meant to cut a file.
Two clicks in rapid succession, usually meant to copy a file or program.

questions.questionText: Which of the following outcomes best describes what happens when a file is copied and pasted?

options.text: The file is deleted, sent to the recycle bin, and moved to a new computer.
The file is deleted and then recreated in a new place using memory fragments.
A copy of the file is placed in memory, and then placed in a new location in the hard drive.
The file is overwritten at a new location and deleted from the old location.

options.text: They would be deleted along with the folder 'Mike's Team'.
They would be moved into 'K:/User' folder.
The folders would remain, but the two .doc files would be deleted.
The .doc files would remain, but the two folders would be deleted.

options.text: The window named 'Untitled - Notepad' will be minimized.
The window named 'Untitled - Notepad' will be closed.
The window named 'Untitled - Notepad' will be maximized.
The window named 'Untitled - Notepad' will be placed behind the 'Word' window.

questions.questionText: What does the Disk Defragmenter utility do?

options.text: Creates a restore point to backup your computer.

questions.questionText: What effect does formatting a hard drive have?

options.text: Deletes all files on the hard drive.

questions.questionText: An email was sent to you and multiple other recipients. What is the most effective method to respond only to the sender of the email?
You have received an email attachment of a file that is on the network. What will happen to the file on the network if you edit the attached file and save it back onto the network?

options.text: The file is overwritten on the network.
The file remains unchanged on the network.
The file is copied and renamed on the network.
The file is saved on the network and also saved locally.

questions.questionText: If a file is stored on the network drive rather than the stored on a local hard drive, which of the following is true?

options.text: Only the network administrator can access the file.
The file has more security measures applied to it.
The file can only be accessed on your computer.
Anyone on the network can access the file.

options.text: A notification is sent to the original sender of the e-mail.
A copy of the e-mail is sent to a designated recipient.
A copy of the e-mail is saved locally on your hard drive.
A file is attached to the email you have just received.

options.text: Everyone in the CC field receives the email before those in the BCC field.
Everyone in the CC field can be identified by recipients.
Everyone in the BCC field can be identified by recipients.
Everyone in the CC and BCC fields cannot reply to the email.

questions.questionText: In the context of Internet usage, what is a "bandwidth limit?"

options.text: A restriction on the range of websites you are able to visit.
A filter to prevent malicious software from infecting your computer.
A restriction on the amount of data that you are able to transmit or receive over a particular Internet connection.
A term used to define the upper limit of traffic possible using a particular technology.

questions.questionText: When transmitting sensitive information on the Internet, how does https compare with http in regards to security?

options.text: https is less than or equally secure
https is more than or equally secure
